## Database Schema

### Tables

| Table | Purpose | Key Constraints |
|---|---|---|
| `profiles` | User profiles (extends auth.users) | `account_tier` CHECK, PK = auth.users FK |
| `analyses` | Squint-test analysis jobs | `input_type` CHECK, `status` CHECK, FK to auth.users |
| `analysis_metrics` | Detailed metric breakdown | FK to analyses |
| `suggestions` | Improvement suggestions | `severity` CHECK, FK to analyses |
| `reports` | Generated reports | FK to analyses + auth.users |

### RLS Policies
All 5 tables have RLS enabled. Policies ensure users can only access their own data:
- **profiles**: SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE own row (matched by `auth.uid() = id`)
- **analyses**: SELECT, INSERT, UPDATE, DELETE own rows (matched by `auth.uid() = user_id`)
- **analysis_metrics/suggestions**: SELECT, INSERT via join to analyses owned by user
- **reports**: SELECT, INSERT, DELETE own rows

### Triggers
- `on_profiles_updated` / `on_analyses_updated`: auto-sets `updated_at = now()` on UPDATE
- `on_auth_user_created`: auto-inserts a `profiles` row when a user signs up, pulling `display_name` and `avatar_url` from user metadata

### Storage
- Bucket **`squint-images`**: private, 10MB limit, image MIME types only
- Per-user folder policies: files stored under `squint-images/{user_id}/...`

## How to Use

```bash
# 1. Navigate to supabase directory
cd supabase

# 2. Copy env template and fill in your secrets
cp .env.example .env
# Edit .env — change ALL passwords, JWT secrets, and API keys

# 3. Start all services
docker compose up -d

# 4. Access Supabase
# Dashboard:  http://localhost:8000  (login with DASHBOARD_USERNAME/PASSWORD)
# API:        http://localhost:8000/rest/v1/
# Database:   localhost:5432  (via Supavisor pooler)
```

> [!IMPORTANT]
> Before deploying, **change every secret** in `.env`. The defaults are insecure demo values.
